note = "Playfair is a transitional design. From the time of enlightenment in the late 18th century, the broad nib quills were replaced by pointed steel pens. This influenced typographical letterforms to become increasingly detached from the written ones. Developments in printing technology, ink and paper making, made it possible to print letterforms of high contrast and fine hairlines. Playfair weights, widths, and optical sizes to cover any typesetting need from the very large to the very small, the delicate to the sturdy.\n\nThis design lends itself to this period, and while it is not a revival of any particular design, it takes influence from the designs of printer and typeface designer John Baskerville, the punch-cutter William Martin\U2019s typeface for the \U201CBoydell Shakespeare\U201D (sic) edition, and from the \U201CScotch Roman\U201D designs that followed thereafter.\n\nPlayfair is well suited for all types of media. It has an extra large x-height and short descenders, that enable it to be set with no leading to conserve space. This is an advantage on both print and screen.\n\nPlayfair includes a full set of small-caps, common ligatures, and discretionary ligatures. All European languages using the latin script are supported. Additionally South-East Asian languages using the Latin script including Vietnamese are supported. Expanded Cyrillic characters allow many languages using the Cyrillic scri";
